The Portland Fire kept pace in the WNBA
playoff hunt at the expense of the Miami Sol.
article.headline: Portland gets key home victory against Miami

images.name: Figgs_Ukari 020727 inline
images.caption: Portland's Ukari Figgs drives past Miami's Claudia Neves during the Fire's 71-61 victory.

article.linkText: Portland wins at home to snap losing streak
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Portland Fire kept pace in the WNBA
playoff hunt at the expense of the Miami Sol.

<photo1>

	   Tamicha Jackson scored 14 points and Sylvia Crawley added 11 as
the Fire beat Miami 71-61 Saturday night to snap a two-game
losing streak.

	   DeMya Walker scored nine points and Alisa Burras added eight for
the Fire (15-11) in Portland's lone home game in between two three-game
road trips.

	   ''We knew this game was very important,'' Crawley said. ''Last
year we did not talk about the playoffs. This year we are
comfortable and talk about it a lot.''

	   Sheri Sam led the Sol (11-14) with 15 points, Betty Lennox added
12, and Sandy Brondello had 11. Miami dropped to 0-2 on its
five-game road trip.

	   ''We were frantic in the first half, just frantic ... there's no
excuse for that,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. ''It's all our
fault. It's my fault, the team's fault, everbody's fault. You can't
play frantic basketball. You're going to lose.''

	   Rothstein said it was a ''good observation'' when asked if he
would make changes to the starting lineup.

	   Portland led by as many as 15 in the first half on the strength
of 51.7 percent shooting and 22 transition points and took a 35-24
lead at halftime. The Sol shot just 34.5 percent and had the ball
stolen five times leading to some easy baskets.

	   ''We just turned the ball over,'' Rothstein said. ''They had 22
points in transition in the first half, and that was the difference
in the game right there.''

	   Portland extended its lead over fifth-place Seattle to 2½
games for the final playoff spot in the Western Conference. Miami
dropped into a three-way tie for fourth in the East with Indiana
and Orlando.

	   ''When we're on defensively I think we're as good as anyone in
the league,'' Fire coach Linda Hargrove said. ''When we play good
defense we have a chance to beat anybody. I really expect this team
to come out and expect to win every game.''

	   Said guard Tully Bevilaqua, whom Hargrove credited with setting
the defensive tone: ''The whole team played so well after losing
two games. It was great to see the team respond like that.''

	   After Portland took a 61-44 lead, the Sol used a 10-2 run to
close to nine points with five minutes left. The Fire played it even
the rest of the way to hold on for the victory.

	   ''Where we are right now, we feel confident,'' Hargrove said.
''I think our team didn't lose any confidence over the two tough
losses.''

	   Portland finished the game at 52.8 percent from the field. The
Sol had a better second half shooting and ended up at 42.1 percent
for the game.

	   ''We just take one game at a time and go to work,'' said Stacey
Thomas, who had three steals. ''When we're aggressive and play our
game, we are one of the best defensive teams in the league.''

	   Vanessa Nygaard, an original member of the Fire who was traded
to Miami during the preseason, scored four points in her first
appearance in Portland since the deal.

	   Rookie Lindsey Yamasaki, a graduate of nearby Oregon City High
School, had seven points in her first professional appearance in
Portland.
